[...]while literature on unfreedom may generally focus on the employment contract, it is not only a question of labor rights and vulnerabilities, but also centrally about (racialized) social exclusion and belonging from the nation.

Under the LSP, employers can recruit workers for any occupation that the federal government defines as "low-skilled."

Since the inception of this program, the most striking growth in TMWs has been in accommodation and food service positions, from 4,360 to 44,740 between 2002 and 2013.20 As I have shown elsewhere, the Tim Hortons corporation recruits most of its temporary labor to western Canada from the Philippines.21 As a labor-sending state, the Philippines has a long history of systematically managing its nationals for overseas work, in its most current form dating back to 1974.

Specifically, Filipino nationals are racially imagined and assembled as "ideal" migrants through a migration apparatus that socializes them to be "exceptional" workers: culturally knowledgeable of the etiquette in host destinations, educated, and yet "cheap."

[...]the Philippines is in the business of devaluing its nationals on an international scale by offering up an essentialist and racially "superior product" at bargain-level prices.

[...]the literature on unfreedom tends to privilege questions of economic structures, employment relations, and the changing dynamics of capitalism to make sense of the plight of vulnerable workers.
